{"id":"1603.00840","submitter":"Daniel Ariad D.A","authors":"Daniel Ariad, Yshai Avishai and Eytan Grosfeld","title":"How vortex bound states affect the Hall conductivity of a chiral $p\\pm i\n  p$ superconductor","comments":"6 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 98, 104511 (2018)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.98.104511","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con cond-mat.stat-mech math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The physics of a planar chiral $p\\pm i p$ superconductor is studied for\nvarious vortex configurations. The occurrence of vortex quasi-particle bound\nstates is exposed together with their ensuing collective properties, such as\nsub-gap bands induced by inter-vortex tunneling. A general method to\ndiagonalize the Hamiltonian of a superconductor in the presence of a vortex\nlattice is developed, that employs only smooth gauge transformations. It\nrenders the Hamiltonian to be periodic (thus allowing the use of a Bloch\ntheorem) and enables the treatment of systems with vortices of finite radii.\nThe pertinent anomalous charge response $c_{xy}$ is calculated (using the\nStreda formula), and reveals that it contains a quantized contribution. This is\nattributed to the response to the nucleation of vortices, from which we deduce\nthe system's quantum phase.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 2 Mar 2016 19:36:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Aug 2018 13:08:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 25 Sep 2018 01:41:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-09-26"}
